{
  "doc_id": "53131",
  "text": "The use of inhibitors and siRNA in our study has not ruled out that other conventional PKCs might also be important in M-CSFinduced NF-kB activation and macrophage survival. In contrast to the actions of PKCa activation of other conventional PKC isoforms, like PKCbI/bII, appear necessary for macrophage apoptosis. The PKCbI/bII isoforms are expressed in apoptotic U937 myelomonocytic cells [CITATION_1] . The human myeloid cell line HL-525 which is devoid of endogenous PKCbII is resistant to TNFa-induced apoptosis [CITATION_2] . Re-expression of PKCbII in HL-525 cells restores their susceptibility to TNFa-induced apoptosis implying that PKCbII is pro-apoptotic and may be required to induce macrophage apoptosis.",
